Ecosystems around the world are experiencing escalating threats including both the loss of consumers and changing disturbance patterns. These changes often act jointly to affect ecosystems: after disturbances, ecosystems undergo succession and consumers can play an integral role in structuring these developing communities.  
<br>  

**For my PhD research, I'm interested in how consumers affect communities as they assemble and recover from disturbances**. *I'm asking the questions: 1) how do large fishes influence coral reef benthic succession and coral recruitment? 2) how do large fishes influence community variability across space and turnover through time during coral reef succession? 3) how do large fishes influence coral recruitment through grazing and grazing scars? and 4) how does herbivore arrival timing influence rocky intertidal succession?* I am using field experiments to tackle my research questions in the Chagos Archipelago, Palmyra Atoll, and Big Sur, California.   
